<HEAD>Rain Widespread After Storms Hit Plains, Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain dampened much of the Eastern Seaboard, Gulf Coast and
Plains early today after severe thunderstorms hit parts of the
Plains and Rockies.
   Thunderstorms on Sunday produced wind gusts near 60 mph at
Abilene, Kan., and Great Falls, Mont., and gusts of about 80 mph
were recorded at Lewiston, Mont. Winds caused some damage in parts
of South Carolina.
   Flooding of small streams was widespread in northeast Colorado
and several roads were washed out, including Highway 6 near Paoli.
   Heavy rain also caused flooding of a highway between Almena and
Cavert, Kan.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ended at 2 a.m. EDT included
just under 2 inches at Meridian, Miss., 1.65 inches at Memphis,
Tenn., and 1.13 inches at Columbia, S.C.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued early today along the East
Coast from southeast New York state to Georgia, in southern Ohio
and West Virginia, in the central Gulf Coast states, from Arkansas
to Nebraska, in parts of Oklahoma and the Texas Panhandle,
northwest New Mexico, central Arizona, northwest Oregon and
southwest Washington.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern New Jersey and southern Pennsylvania across North
Carolina, from the Ohio Valley across the Tennessee Valley, central
and southern Missouri, much of Louisiana, Mississippi, western and
southern Alabama, Florida's Panhandle and Gulf Coast, northern
Colorado, central and northern Arizona, southwest Montana, and from
northwest Oregon into southwest Washington.
   Highs were expected to be in the upper 60s along parts of the
Pacific Coast; the 70s to near 80 in the remainder of the northern
and central Pacific Coast, over southwest California, from New
England across Virginia, over the Great Lakes and the upper Ohio
Valley; the 70s and low 80s from central Colorado across northwest
New Mexico and the higher elevations of Arizona; near 100 degrees
in eastern Montana and central Texas; and from 100 to near 110
degrees in the Desert Southwest. Highs elsewhere generally were
expected to be in the 80s and 90s.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 42 degrees at Houlton,
Maine, to 93 degrees at Blythe, Calif., Las Vegas and Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 75 cloudy; Boston 62 fair; Buffalo 59 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 76 foggy; Cincinnati 71 foggy; Cleveland 63
cloudy; Detroit 60 fair; Miami 81 partly cloudy; New York 66 rain;
Philadelphia 65 cloudy; Portland, Maine 58 fair; Washington 70 rain.
   _Central: Bismarck 66 fair; Chicago 70 foggy; Dallas-Fort Worth
80 fair; Denver 58 fair; Des Moines 73 foggy; Indianapolis 73
foggy; Kansas City 71 thunderstorm; Minneapolis-St. Paul 69 cloudy;
Nashville 73 fair; New Orleans 76 fair; St. Louis 74 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 67 partly cloudy; Anchorage 56 cloudy; Las
Vegas 94 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 64 fair; Phoenix 92 partly
cloudy; Salt Lake City 80 fair; San Diego 67 fair; San Francisco 57
windy; Seattle 62 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 63 fair; Toronto 57 fair.
</TEXT>
